# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: banting-boat
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh is where the spread of Islam in Indonesia began.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] It was a key location for the spread of Islam in Southeast Asia more broadly.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Islam reached Aceh (Kingdoms of Fansur and Lamuri) around 1250.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In the early 17th century, the Aceh Sultanate was the wealthiest, most powerful, and most cultivated state in the Strait of Malacca.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh has a history of political independence and resistance to control by outsiders, including the former Dutch East Indies and later the Indonesian governments.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh has substantial natural resources of oil and natural gas.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh was the closest point of land to the epicenter of the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami, which devastated much of the western coast of the province.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Approximately 170,000 Indonesians were killed or went missing in the disaster.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The disaster helped precipitate the peace agreement between the government of Indonesia and the separatist group of Free Aceh Movement.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Upon its formation in 1956 it bore the name **Aceh** before being renamed to the **Daerah Istimewa Aceh** (Special Region of Aceh; 1959–2001), **Nanggroe Aceh Darussalam** (2001–2009), and back to **Aceh** (2009–present).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In the past it was also spelled as *Acheh*, *Atjeh*, and *Achin*.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] According to several archaeological findings, the first evidence of human habitation in Aceh is from a site near the Tamiang River, where shell middens are present.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Stone tools and faunal remains were also found on the site.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Archeologists believe the site was first occupied around 10,000 BCE.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The history of Aceh stretches back to the Lambri Kingdom.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Several documented references indicate that Hindu-Buddhist culture existed in the area before its Islamization.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The people of Lambri were described by Marco Polo as "idolaters", who had a maharaja as their ruler (a king in the Hindu political structure), likely meaning they were Hindus, Buddhists, or a combination thereof.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The inscription at Tanjore of Rajendra I documents the conquest of a land called "llämuridesam", located at the northern tip of Sumatra.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The *Nagarakretagama* documents the possessions of the Imperial Majapahit and states that it controls Barat (identified as the western coast of Aceh).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Chinese records indicate that Aceh was under the control of the Sriwijaya.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Though many temples were left abandoned or converted into mosques, such as the Indrapuri Old Mosque, some evidence remains, such as the head of a stone sculpture of Avalokiteshvara Boddhisattva that was discovered in Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Images of Amitabha Buddhas adorn his crown, facing forward and on each side.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Srivijayan art estimated 9th-century CE collection of National Museum of Indonesia, Jakarta.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] One of the few remaining structures is the Indra Patra fort, which houses several Hindu shrines.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Historic names such as Indrapurba, Indrapurwa, Indrapatra, and Indrapuri, which refer to the god Indra, also indicate that Hinduism had a lasting and significant presence in this land.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Evidence concerning the arrival and subsequent establishment of Islam in Southeast Asia is thin and inconclusive.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The historian Anthony Reid has argued that the region of the Cham people on the south-central coast of Vietnam was one of the earliest Islamic centers in Southeast Asia.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Furthermore, as the Cham people fled the Vietnamese, one of the earliest locations where they established a relationship was with Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] It is thought that one of the earliest centers of Islam was in the Aceh region.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] When Venetian traveler Marco Polo passed by Sumatra on his way home from China in 1292, he found that Peureulak was a Muslim town while nearby "Basma(n)" and "Samara" were not.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] "Basma(n)" and "Samara" are often said to be Pasai and Samudra, but evidence is inconclusive.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The gravestone of Sultan Malikussaleh, the first Muslim ruler of Samudra, has been found and is dated AH 696 (1297 CE).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This is the earliest clear evidence of a Muslim dynasty in the Indonesia-Malay area, and more 13th-century gravestones show that this region continued under Muslim rule.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Ibn Batutah, a Moroccan traveller, passing through on his way to China in 1345 and 1346, found that the ruler of Samudra was a follower of the Shafi'i school of Islam.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] After Islam first appeared in Aceh, it spread into the coastal regions by the 15th century.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh soon became a cultural and scholastic Islamic center throughout Southeast Asia.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] It also became wealthy because it was a center of extensive trade.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Portuguese apothecary Tome Pires reported in his early 16th-century book *Suma Oriental* that most of the kings of Sumatra, from Aceh to Palembang, were Muslim.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] At Pasai, in what is now the North Aceh Regency, there was a thriving international port.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Pires attributed the establishment of Islam in Pasai to the 'cunning' of the Muslim merchants.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The ruler of Pasai, however, had not been able to convert the people of the interior.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Sultanate of Aceh was established by Sultan Ali Mughayat Syah in 1511.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] João Ribeiro Gaio, based on information provided by a former captive called Diogo Gil, wrote the "Roteiro das Cousas do Achem" (Lisboa 1997)—a description of the sultanate.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Later, during its golden era, in the 17th century, its territory and political influence expanded as far as Satun in southern Thailand, Johor in Malay Peninsula, and Siak in what is today the province of Riau.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] As was the case with most non-Javan pre-colonial states, Acehnese power expanded outward by sea rather than inland.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] As it expanded down the Sumatran coast, its main competitors were Johor and Portuguese Malacca on the other side of the Straits of Malacca.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] It was this seaborne trade focus that led Aceh to rely on rice imports from north Java rather than develop self-sufficiency in rice production.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] After the Portuguese occupation of Malacca in 1511, many Islamic traders passing the Malacca Straits shifted their trade to Banda Aceh and increased the Acehnese rulers' wealth.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] During the reign of Sultan Iskandar Muda in the 17th century, Aceh's influence extended to most of Sumatra and the Malay Peninsula.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh allied itself with the Ottoman Empire and the Dutch East India Company in their struggle against the Portuguese and the Johor Sultanate.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Acehnese military power waned gradually thereafter, and Aceh ceded its territory of Pariaman in Sumatra to the Dutch in the 18th century.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] By the early 19th century, however, Aceh had become an increasingly influential power due to its strategic location for controlling regional trade.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In the 1820s, it was the producer of over half the world's supply of black pepper.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The pepper trade produced new wealth for the sultanate and for the rulers of many smaller nearby ports that had been under Aceh's control, but were now able to assert more independence.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] These changes initially threatened Aceh's integrity, but a new Sultan, Tuanku Ibrahim, who ruled from 1838 to 1870, reasserted control over nearby ports.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Under the Anglo-Dutch Treaty of 1824, the British ceded their colonial possessions on Sumatra to the Dutch.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In the treaty, the British described Aceh as one of their possessions, although they had no actual control over the sultanate.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Initially, under the agreement, the Dutch agreed to respect Aceh's independence.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In 1871, however, the British dropped previous opposition to a Dutch invasion of Aceh, possibly to prevent France or the United States from gaining a foothold in the region.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Although neither the Dutch nor the British knew the specifics, there had been rumors since the 1850s that Aceh had been in communication with the rulers of France and of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Pirates operating from Aceh threatened commerce in the Strait of Malacca; the sultan was unable to control them.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Britain was a protector of Aceh and permitted the Netherlands to eradicate the pirates.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The campaign quickly drove out the sultan, but the local leaders mobilized and fought the Dutch in four decades of guerrilla war, with high levels of atrocities.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Dutch colonial government declared war on Aceh on 26 March 1873.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh sought American help, but Washington rejected the request.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Dutch tried one strategy after another over the course of four decades.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] An expedition under Major General Johan Harmen Rudolf Köhler in 1873 occupied most of the coastal areas.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Köhler's strategy was to attack and take the sultan's palace.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Dutch then tried a naval blockade, reconciliation, concentration within a line of forts, and lastly passive containment.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Reaching 15 to 20 million guilders a year, the heavy spending for failed strategies nearly bankrupted the colonial government.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] During the course of the war, the Dutch set up the Gouvernment of Atjeh and Dependencies under a governor, although it did not establish wider control of its territory until after 1908.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Aceh army was rapidly modernized, and Aceh soldiers killed Köhler.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Köhler made some grave tactical errors, and the reputation of the Dutch was severely harmed.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In recent years, in line with expanding international attention to human rights issues and atrocities in war zones, there has been increasing discussion about some of the recorded acts of cruelty and slaughter committed by Dutch troops during the period of warfare in Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Hasan Mustafa (1852–1930) was a chief *penghulu* (judge) for the colonial government, stationed in Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] He had to balance traditional Muslim justice with Dutch law.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] To stop the Aceh rebellion, Hasan Mustafa issued a fatwa, telling the Muslim population there in 1894, "It is Incumbent upon the Indonesian Muslim to be loyal to the Dutch East Indies Government".
[src:banting-boat/aceh] During World War II, Japanese troops occupied Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Acehnese *ulama* (Islamic clerics) fought against both the Dutch and the Japanese, revolting against the Dutch in February 1942 and against Japan in November 1942.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The revolt was led by the All-Aceh Religious Scholars' Association (PUSA).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Japanese suffered 18 dead in the uprising while they slaughtered up to 100 or over 120 Acehnese.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The revolt happened in Bayu and was centered around Tjot Plieng village's religious school.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] During the revolt, the Japanese troops armed with mortars and machine guns were charged by sword wielding Acehnese under Teungku Abduldjalil (Tengku Abdul Djalil) in Buloh Gampong Teungah and Tjot Plieng on 10 and 13 November.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In May 1945 the Acehnese rebelled again.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The religious ulama party gained ascendancy to replace district warlords (*ulèebalang*) party that formerly collaborated with the Dutch.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Concrete bunkers still line the northernmost beaches.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] After World War II, civil war erupted in 1945 between the district warlords party, which supported the return of a Dutch government, and the Persatuan Ulama Seluruh Aceh (PUSA) party, which supported the newly proclaimed state of Indonesia.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The ulama won, and the area remained free during the Indonesian War of Independence.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Dutch military itself never attempted to invade Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The civil war raised the religious *ulama* party leader, Daud Bereu'eh, to the position of military governor of Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Acehnese revolted soon after their inclusion into an independent Indonesia, a situation created by a complex mix of what the Acehnese regarded as transgressions against and betrayals of their rights.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Sukarno, the first president of Indonesia, had reneged on his promise made on 16 June 1948 that Aceh would be allowed to rule itself in accordance with Islamic Law.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh was politically dismantled and incorporated into the province of North Sumatra in 1950.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This resulted in the Acehnese Rebellion of 1953–59, which was led by Daud Beureu'eh, who on 20 September 1953 declared a free, independent Aceh under the leadership of Sekarmadji Maridjan Kartosoewirjo.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In 1959, the Indonesian government attempted to placate the Acehnese by offering broad freedom in matters of religion, education, and culture.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] During the 1970s, under an agreement with the Indonesian central government, American oil and gas companies began the exploitation of Aceh's natural resources.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Alleged unequal distribution of profits between the central government and the native people of Aceh induced Dr.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Hasan Muhammad di Tiro, former ambassador of Darul Islam, to call for an independent Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The movement had a small number of followers initially, and di Tiro himself had to live in exile in Sweden.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Meanwhile, the province followed Suharto's policy of economic development and industrialization.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] During the late 1980s, several security incidents prompted the Indonesian central government to take repressive measures and to send troops to Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Human rights abuse was rampant for the next decade, resulting in many grievances on the part of the Acehnese toward the Indonesian central government.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In 1990, the Indonesian government initiated military operations against GAM by deploying more than 12,000 Indonesian troops in the region.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] During the late 1990s, chaos in Java and an ineffective central government gave an advantage to the Free Aceh Movement and resulted in the second phase of the rebellion, this time with large support from the Acehnese people.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This support was demonstrated during the 1999 plebiscite in Banda Aceh, which was attended by nearly half a million people (out of the province's four million population).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Indonesian central government responded in 2001 by broadening Aceh's autonomy, giving its government the right to apply Sharia law more broadly and the right to receive direct foreign investment.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This was again accompanied by repressive measures, however, and in 2003 an offensive began and a state of emergency was proclaimed in the province.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The war was still ongoing when the tsunami disaster of 2004 struck the province.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In 2001, villagers from the North Aceh Regency sued ExxonMobil for human rights abuses at the hands of Indonesian military units hired by the company for security for its natural gas operations.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] ExxonMobil denied fault for the allegations.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] After a series of attacks against its operations, the company shut down its Arun natural gas operations in the province.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The western coastal areas of Aceh, including the cities of Banda Aceh, Calang, and Meulaboh, were among the areas hardest hit by the tsunami resulting from the magnitude 9.2 Indian Ocean earthquake on 26 December 2004.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] While estimates vary, over 170,000 people were killed by the tsunami in Aceh, and about 500,000 were left homeless.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The tragedy of the tsunami was further compounded several months later, when the 2005 M8.6 Nias–Simeulue earthquake struck the seabed between the islands of Simeulue Island in Aceh and Nias in North Sumatra.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This second quake killed a further 1346 people on Nias and Simeulue, displaced tens of thousands more, and caused the tsunami response to be expanded to include Nias.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The World Health Organisation estimates a 100% increase in prevalence of mild and moderate mental disorders in Aceh's general population after the tsunami.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Pacific Tsunami Warning Center, misjudging the intensity of the Sumatra earthquake, issued a bulletin stating that no tsunami was expected following a magnitude 8.0 quake, based on historical data.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Only when more accurate measurements of quakes of magnitude 9.0 or higher became available did scientists at the warning center realize they were dealing with a basin-wide tsunami across the Indian Ocean.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] When the tsunami hit, it was enormous, and the death toll in Aceh exceeded 100,000.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] There was no tsunami warning system in 2004.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Tsunami warning systems have improved since the immense death toll drew international attention, but in rural areas where many lack internet access or cell phones, it remains a challenge to communicate warnings promptly.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] A warning system was put in place at the request of Aceh residents, but it was disabled in 2007 after technical issues and a false alarm that caused a panic.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The population of Aceh before the December 2004 tsunami was 4,271,000 (2004).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] As of February 2006, more than a year after the tsunami, a large number of people were still living in barrack-style temporary living centers (TLC) or tents.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Reconstruction was visible everywhere, but due to the sheer scale of the disaster and logistic difficulties, progress was slow.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] A study in 2007 estimated that 83.6% of the population had a psychiatric illness, while 69.8% suffers from severe emotional distress.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The ramifications of the tsunami went beyond the immediate impact on the lives and infrastructure of the Acehnese living on the coast.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Since the disaster, the Acehnese rebel movement GAM, which had been fighting for independence against the Indonesian authorities for 29 years, has signed a peace deal (15 August 2005).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The perception that the tsunami was punishment for insufficient piety in this proudly Muslim province is partly behind the increased emphasis on the importance of religion post-tsunami.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This has been most evident in the increased implementation of Sharia law, including the introduction of the controversial Wilayatul Hisbah (Syariah police).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] As homes are being built and people's basic needs are met, the people are also looking to improve the quality of education, increase tourism, and develop a responsible, sustainable industry.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Well-qualified educators are in high demand in Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] While parts of the capital Banda Aceh were unscathed, the areas closest to the water, especially the areas of Kampung Jawa and Meuraxa, were completely destroyed.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Most of the rest of the western coast of Aceh was severely damaged.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Other towns on Aceh's west coast hit by the disaster included Lhoknga, Leupung, Lamno, Patek, Calang, Teunom, and the island of Simeulue.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Affected or destroyed towns on the region's north and east coasts were Pidie Regency, Samalanga, and Lhokseumawe.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The area was slowly rebuilt after the disaster.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The government initially proposed the creation of a two-kilometer buffer zone along low-lying coastal areas within which permanent construction was not permitted.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This proposal was unpopular among some local residents and proved impractical in most situations, especially among fishing families that depend on living near the sea.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Indonesian government established a special agency for Aceh reconstruction, the Badan Rehabilitasi dan Rekonstruksi (BRR), headed by Kuntoro Mangkusubroto, a former Indonesian government minister.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This agency had ministry-level authority and incorporated officials, professionals, and community leaders from all backgrounds.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Most of the reconstruction work was performed by local people using a mix of traditional methods and partially prefabricated structures, with funding from many international organizations, governments, and individuals, as well as the people themselves.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Government of Indonesia estimated in their Preliminary Damage and Losses Assessment that damages amounted to US$4.5 billion (before inflation, and US$6.2 billion including inflation).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Three years after the tsunami, reconstruction was still ongoing.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The World Bank monitored funding for reconstruction in Aceh and reported that US$7.7 billion had been earmarked for the reconstruction, whilst in June 2007, US$5.8 billion had been allocated to specific reconstruction projects, of which US$3.4 billion had actually been spent (58%).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In 2009, the government opened a US$5.6 million museum to commemorate the tsunami with photographs, stories, and a simulation of the earthquake that triggered the tsunami.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The 2004 tsunami helped trigger a peace agreement between the GAM and the Indonesian government.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The mood in post-Suharto Indonesia during the liberal-democratic reform period, along with changes in the Indonesian military, helped create an environment more favorable to peace talks.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The roles of newly elected president Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono and vice president Jusuf Kalla were highly significant.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] At the same time, the GAM leadership was undergoing changes, and the Indonesian military had inflicted so much damage on the rebel movement that it had little choice but to negotiate with the central government.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The peace talks were first initiated by Juha Christensen, a Finnish peace activist, and then formally facilitated by a Finland-based NGO, the Crisis Management Initiative led by former Finnish president Martti Ahtisaari.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The resulting peace agreement, generally known as the Helsinki Agreement, was signed on 15 August 2005.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Under the agreement, Aceh would receive special autonomy, and government troops would be withdrawn from the province in exchange for GAM's disarmament.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] As part of the agreement, the European Union dispatched Aceh Monitoring Mission.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Their mission expired on 15 December 2006, following local elections.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh has been granted greater autonomy through an Aceh government law that includes special rights agreed in 2006 as well as the right of Acehnese people to establish local political parties to represent their interests.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Human rights advocates protest that previous human rights violations in the province have not been seriously addressed.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In 2014, there were 460 Sumatran elephants in Aceh including at least eight baby elephants.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The area has been suffering from deforestation since the 1970s.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The first wood pulp mill in Aceh was built in 1982.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The government of Aceh intends a law by which 1.2 million hectares would be opened for commercial use.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Coastal waters off Aceh fall within Fisheries Management Area 572 (WPP 572), where the Blue Halo S pilot—involving Konservasi Indonesia—has focused on improving marine management and resilience outcomes.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Within the country, Aceh is governed not as a regular province but as a special autonomous province (*daerah istimewa*), an administrative designation intended to give the area increased autonomy from the central government in Jakarta.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This has resulted in canings for crimes deemed to have violated *Sharia*, such as gambling, drinking, skipping Friday prayers, and most notably homosexuality.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Regional elections have been held in Aceh in recent years for senior positions at the provincial, regency (*kabupaten*) and district (*kecamatan*) levels.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In the 2006 elections, Irwandi Yusuf was elected as the provincial governor for 2007–2012; in the elections in April 2012, Zaini Abdullah was elected as governor for 2012–2017.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Beginning with the promulgation of Law 44/1999, Aceh's governor began to issue limited *Sharia*-based regulations—for example, requiring female government employees to wear Islamic dress.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The frequency of attacks on individuals considered to be violating shariatic principles appeared to increase following the enactment of Law 44/1999 and the governor's *Sharia* regulations.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In 2014, a group of scholars calling themselves the *Tadzkiiratul Ummah* began attacking and painting the pants of men and women as a call for heavier Islamic law enforcement in the area.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Upon the enactment of the Special Autonomy Law in 2001, Aceh's provincial legislature enacted a series of *qanuns* (local laws) governing the implementation of *Sharia*.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] With the exception of gambling, none of the practices are prohibited outside of Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Responsibility for enforcement of the *qanun*s rests both with the Indonesian National Police and with a special Islamic religious police force unique to Aceh known as the Wilayatul Hisbah (Sharia Authority).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] All of the *qanun*s provide for penalties including fines, imprisonment, and caning, the latter a punishment unknown in most parts of Indonesia.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Between mid-2005 and early 2007, at least 135 people were caned in Aceh for transgressing the *qanun*s.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In April 2016, a 60-year-old non-Muslim woman was sentenced to 30 lashes for selling alcoholic drinks.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The controversy was *qanun* enforcement did not apply to non-Muslims, with only national law, as in the rest of Indonesia, applying.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In April 2009, the Aceh Party won control of the local parliament in Aceh's first post-war legislative elections.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In September 2009, one month before the new legislators were to take office, the outgoing parliament unanimously endorsed two new *qanun*s to expand the existing criminal *Sharia* framework in Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] One bill, the *Qanun on Criminal Procedure* (*Qanun Hukum Jinayat*), was intended to create an entirely new procedural code for the enforcement of *Sharia* by police, prosecutors, and courts in Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The law authorized punishments, including up to 60 lashes for "intimacy," up to 100 lashes for engaging in homosexual conduct, up to 100 lashes for adultery by unmarried persons, and death by stoning for adultery by a married person.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] However, the then-proposed laws were met with widespread condemnation across Indonesia, and then-governor Irwandi Yusuf refused to sign them, thereby leaving them without legal force, rather than actual laws.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In March 2013, the Aceh government removed the stoning provision from its own draft of a new criminal code.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In practice, since the introduction of the new laws, there has been a considerable increase in the use of the allowable penalties.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] As an example, in August 2015, six men in Bireuën Regency were arrested and caned for betting on the names of passing buses.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] On 18 September 2015, a total of 34 people were caned in Banda Aceh and in the nearby regency of Aceh Besar.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Two gay men are to be publicly lashed 85 times each under *Sharia* law after being filmed by vigilantes in Indonesia.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] An Islamic court in the province of Aceh passed down its first sentence for homosexuality on the International Day Against Homophobia and Transphobia, 17 May 2017, in spite of international appeals to spare the couple.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Whipping is the common *hudud* punishment for gambling, adultery, drinking alcohol, and having gay or premarital sex.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Typically, the whipping has been done by men.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In 2020, with increased enforcement and more crimes being committed by women, Aceh authorities noted the government was trying to follow Islamic law, which calls for women to be whipped by female perpetrators.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Administratively, the province is subdivided into eighteen regencies (Indonesian: *kabupaten*; Acehnese: *kabupatèn*) and five autonomous cities (Indonesian: *kota*; Acehnese: *banda*).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The capital and the largest city is Banda Aceh, located on the coast near the northern tip of Sumatra.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] When originally devised in 1956, the province comprised the city of Banda Aceh and six regencies: Great Aceh, Pidie, North Aceh, East Aceh, Central Aceh, and West Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] However, on 14 November 1956, a seventh regency (South Aceh) was created from the southeastern districts of West Aceh Regency.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Bener Meriah Regency was created on 19 December 2003 (from part of Central Aceh Regency), and Pidie Jaya Regency (from part of Pidie Regency) and Subulussalam City (from part of Aceh Singkil Regency) on 2 January 2007.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Some other local areas are pushing to create new autonomous areas, usually with the stated goal of enhancing local control over politics and development.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The cities and regencies (subdivided into the 289 districts or *kecamatan* of Aceh), are listed below with their areas and their populations at the 2010 census and the 2020 census, together with the officially estimated population as of mid 2024.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh is unique in Indonesia in grouping its villages into *mukim*s.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] These are sometimes related to traditional indigenous communities.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Beginning in September 2023, the Indonesian government provided legal recognition to the claims of some *mukim*s over customary forests.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The province comprises two of Indonesia's 84 national electoral districts to elect members to the People's Representative Council.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In 2006, the economy of Aceh grew by 7.7% after having minimal growth since the devastating tsunami.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This growth was primarily driven by the reconstruction effort with massive growth in the building/construction sector.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The ending of the conflict, and the reconstruction program resulted in the structure of the economy changing significantly since 2003.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Service sectors played a more dominant role whilst the share of the oil and gas sectors continued to decline.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] After peaking at around 40% in December 2005, largely as a result of the Dutch disease impact of sudden aid flows into the province, inflation declined steadily and was 8.5% in June 2007, close to the national level in Indonesia of 5.7%.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Persistent inflation means that Aceh's consumer price index (CPI) remains the highest in Indonesia.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] As a result, Aceh's cost competitiveness has declined as reflected in both inflation and wage data.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Although inflation has slowed down, CPI has registered steady increases since the tsunami.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Using 2002 as a base, Aceh's CPI increased to 185.6 (June 2007) while the national CPI increased to 148.2.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] There have been relatively large nominal wage increases in particular sectors, such as construction where, on average, workers' nominal wages have risen to almost Rp.60,000 per day, from Rp.29,000 pre-tsunami.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This is also reflected in Aceh's minimum regional wage (UMR, or Upah Minimum Regional), which increased by 55% from Rp.550,000 pre-tsunami to Rp.850,000 in 2007, compared with an increase of 42% in neighboring North Sumatra, from Rp.537,000 to Rp.761,000.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Poverty levels increased slightly in Aceh in 2005 after the tsunami, but by less than expected.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The poverty level then fell in 2006 to below the pre-tsunami level, suggesting that the rise in tsunami-related poverty was short lived and reconstruction activities and the end of the conflict most probably facilitated this decline.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] However, poverty in Aceh remains significantly higher than in the rest of Indonesia.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] A large number of the Acehnese remain vulnerable to poverty, reinforcing the need for further sustained efforts at development in the post-tsunami construction period.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The population of Aceh was not adequately documented during the Indonesia 2000 census because the insurgency complicated the process of collecting accurate information.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] An estimated 170,000 people died in Aceh in the 2004 tsunami which further complicates the task of careful demographic analysis.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The official estimate for mid 2023 was 5,482,527 (comprising 2,753,176 males and 2,729,351 females); however, the sum of the official population estimates for the individual regencies and cities totalled 5,512,219 people.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh is a diverse region occupied by several ethnic and language groups.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] There are also significant populations of Chinese and Javanese.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Among the present-day population of Aceh, especially in coastal areas, one can find a number of individuals of Arab, Turkish, Portuguese, and Indian descent.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Acehnese language is widely spoken within the Acehnese population.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This is a member of the Aceh-Chamic group of languages, whose other representatives are mostly found in Vietnam and Cambodia, and is also closely related to the Malay group of languages.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Acehnese also has many words borrowed from Malay and Arabic and traditionally was written using Arabic script.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Acehnese is also used as local language in Langkat and Asahan (North Sumatra), and Kedah (Malaysia), and once dominated Penang.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aside from the Indonesian language, Acehnese is also designated as the co-official regional language of Aceh under Qanun Number 10 of 2022.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Alas and Kluet are closely related languages within the Batak group.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Jamee language originated from Minangkabau language in West Sumatra, with just a few variations and differences.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] According to 2022 data of the Ministry of Religious Affairs, Aceh is overwhelmingly Muslim-majority where they dominate Aceh with more than 98%.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] While the rest 1.15% of population are Protestants, 0.13% Buddhists and 0.1% Catholics.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Religious issues are often sensitive in Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] There is very strong support for Islam across the province, and sometimes other religious groups – such as Christians or Buddhists – feel that they are subject to social or community pressure to limit their activities.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The official explanation for this action, supported by both the governor of Aceh Zaini Abdullah and the Indonesian home affairs minister Gamawan Fauzi from Jakarta, was that the churches did not have the appropriate permits.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Earlier in April 2012, a number of churches in the Singkil regency in southern Aceh had also been ordered to close.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In response, some Christians voiced concern about these actions.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In 2015 a church was burned down and another attacked in which a Muslim rioter was shot, causing President Joko Widodo to call for calm.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Caning has increasingly been used as a form of judicial punishment in Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] At least 72 people were caned for various offences, including drinking alcohol, being alone with someone of the opposite sex who was not a marriage partner or relative (khalwat), gambling and for being caught having gay sex.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The Acehnese authorities passed a series of by-laws governing the implementation of Sharia after the enactment of the province's Special Autonomy Law in 2001.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In 2016 alone, 100 public caning cases were documented by human rights organizations.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In January 2018, the Aceh police, with support from the Aceh autonomous government, raided hair salons known to have LGBT clients and staff as part of an *operasi penyakit masyarakat* ("community sickness operation").
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The police abused all LGBT citizens within the premises of the parlors and arrested twelve transgender women.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The arrested trans women were stripped topless, had their heads shaved, and were forced to chant insults at themselves as part of a process "until they really become men".
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The intent of the incident was to reverse what officials deemed a "social disease" and that parents were coming to them upset at the increasing number of LGBT individuals in Aceh.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The event was decried by human rights organizations local and worldwide, such as Amnesty International.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh has many tourist destinations, especially natural, historical and cultural tourism.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh has a variety of distinctive arts and culture.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In addition to rencong, the Acehnese people also possessed several other special weapons, such as sikin panyang, peurise awe, peurise teumaga, siwah, geuliwang and peudeueng.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh's traditional house is called *Rumoh Aceh*.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] This house is a type of house on stilts with three main parts and one additional section.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The three main parts of the Aceh house are the *seuramoë keuë* (front porch), *seuramoë teungoh* (middle porch) and *seuramoë likôt* (back porch).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Another additional part is the *rumoh dapu* (kitchen house).
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Traditional Acehnese dances illustrate traditional heritage, religion, and local folklore.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Acehnese dances are generally performed in groups, in which a group of dancers are of the same sex, and there are standing or sitting positions.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] When viewed from the accompanying music, the dances can be grouped into two types; namely accompanied by the vocal and percussion of the dancer's own body, and accompanied by an ensemble of musical instruments.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Some dances that are famous at the national and even world level are dances originating from Aceh, such as the Rateb Meuseukat Dance and the Saman dance.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Acehnese cuisine uses combinations of spices found in Indian and Arabic cuisine, include ginger, pepper, coriander, cumin, cloves, cinnamon, cardamom, and fennel.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] A variety of Acehnese foods are cooked with curry or curry spices and coconut milk, which are generally combined with meat, such as buffalo meat, beef, lamb, fish and chicken.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Certain recipes have traditionally used cannabis as a seasoning; which is also found in some other Southeast Asian dishes such as in Laos, but now the material is no longer used.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Dishes native to Aceh include nasi gurih, mie aceh, mie caluk and timphan.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Aceh has a tradition of oral literature, such as the folktales *The king of the parakeets* and *Banta Berensyah*.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The oldest Acehnese manuscripts that can be found are from 1069 H (1658/1659 AD), namely Hikayat Seuma'un.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Before Dutch colonialism (1873–1942), almost all Acehnese literature was in the form of poetry known as Hikayat.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Very little is in the form of prose and one of them is the Book of Bakeu Meunan which is a translation of the book Qawaa'id al-Islaam.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] It was only after the arrival of the Dutch that Acehnese writings appeared in the form of prose, in the 1930s, such as Lhee Saboh Nang written by Aboe Bakar and De Vries.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] It was only afterward that various forms of prose appeared, but still remained dominated by the form of Hikayat.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] The 74-km Sigli–Banda Aceh Toll Road is currently under construction, as a part of the Trans-Sumatra Toll Road.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Railways in Aceh has started since the Dutch colonial era.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] In 1876 the Royal Netherlands East Indies Army (KNIL) started to build a 750-mm gauge railways known as Atjeh Tram, which began operating from 1882 to 1942 and later changed its name to Atjeh Staatsspoorwegen (ASS) in 1916.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Its railways assets, now mostly inactive, is under the ownership of the Regional Division I North Sumatra and Aceh of Kereta Api Indonesia.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Cut Meutia (train) is a train that serves Krueng Geukueh to Krueng Mane in North Aceh Regency.
[src:banting-boat/aceh] Airports in Aceh include Sultan Iskandar Muda International Airport in Aceh Besar Regency (serving Banda Aceh and surrounding areas) and Maimun Saleh Airport in Sabang.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The **Admiralty Islands** are an archipelago group of 40 islands in the Bismarck Archipelago, to the north of New Guinea in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] These are also sometimes known as the **Manus Islands**, after the largest island of the chain.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] These rainforest-covered islands constitute Manus Province, the smallest and least-populous province of Papua New Guinea, in its Islands Region.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The province had a population of 60,485 at the 2011 Census.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Many of the smaller Admiralty Islands are atolls and uninhabited.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The larger islands in the center of the group are Manus Island and Los Negros Island.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The other larger islands are Tong Island, Pak Island, Rambutyo Island and Lou Island to the east, Mbuke Island to the south and Bipi Island to the west of Manus Island.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Baluan Island, to the south of Manus Island, is the main island of the Pam Islands, where the Baluan-Pam language is spoken.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Other islands that have been noted as significant places in the history of Manus include Ndrova Island, Pityilu Island and Ponam Island.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The temperature of the Admiralty Islands varies little throughout the year, reaching daily highs of 30–32 °C (86–90 °F) and 20–24 °C (68–75 °F) at night.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Average annual rainfall is 3,382 mm (133 in) and is somewhat seasonal, with June–August being the wettest months.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Manus reaches an elevation of 700 m (2,300 ft) and is volcanic in origin and probably broke through the ocean's surface in the late Miocene, 8–10 million years ago.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The substrate of the island is either directly volcanic or from uplifted coral limestone.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The main town in the islands is Lorengau on Manus, connected by road to an airport on nearby Los Negros Island, otherwise transport around the islands is by boat.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] There is little tourism, although the seas are attractive to divers, including Jean-Michel Cousteau who spent time on nearby Wuvulu Island in the 1970s.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Due to the isolated location, the rain forests of the Admiralty Islands are home to rare and endemic species of birds, bats and other animals, and are considered a separate ecoregion, the **Admiralty Islands lowland rain forests**.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The majority of the forests on Manus still remain, but some of the smaller islands have been cleared for coconut farming.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The typical tree species are various *Calophyllum* and *Sararanga* species.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The 58.5 km2 (22.6 sq mi) Ndrolowa Wildlife Management Area was created in March 1985 south of Lorengau on Manus Island and contains both terrestrial and marine regions.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] A further 240 km2 (93 sq mi) protected area has been established around the highest mountain on Manus, Mount Dremsel, but the level of protection remains undetermined in the UNEP World Database on Protected Areas.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Three of the bird species endemic to Admiralty Islands have been listed as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List: Manus fantail (*Rhipidura semirubra*), superb pitta (*Pitta superba*) and Manus masked owl (*Tyto manusi*), and the Manus dwarf kingfisher (*Ceyx dispar*) listed as near threatened.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Three other birds are endemic to Admiralty Islands but are classified as non-threatened or least concern: white-naped friarbird (*Philemon albitorques*), Manus monarch (*Monarcha infelix*) and Manus hawk owl (*Ninox meeki*).
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The islands are home to two endemic *Cornufer* frogs (*Cornufer admiraltiensis* and *Cornufer latro*) and four lizards, while the emerald green snail of Manus was the first terrestrial snail to be listed as vulnerable by the IUCN.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Along with New Guinea, the Bismarck Archipelago and the Solomon Islands Archipelago, the Admiralty Islands were first inhabited approximately 40,000 years ago, in the initial wave of migration out of Southeast Asia that also populated Australia.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] This early society appears to have cultivated taro, and to have deliberately introduced wild animals from New Guinea such as bandicoots and large rats.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Obsidian was gathered and traded throughout the Admiralty Islands archipelago.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The Lapita culture arose around 3,500 years ago, and its extent ranged from the Admiralty Islands to Tonga and Samoa.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Its origins are contested, but it may well have been a product of another wave of migration from Southeast Asia.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Lapita society featured renowned pottery, stilt houses, the introduction of domestic animals such as pigs, dogs, and chickens, and substantial developments in agriculture and boat technology, allowing long-distance trade to develop.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Lapita society, as a distinct culture and extended trade network, collapsed around 2,000 years ago.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The first European to visit the islands was the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Saavedra when trying to return from Tidore to New Spain in the summer of 1528.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Saavedra charted Manus as *Urays la Grande*.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Its visit was also reported in 1616 by the Dutch navigator Willem Schouten.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] The name 'Admiralty Islands' was devised by Captain Philip Carteret of the British Royal Navy in 1767.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Between 1884 and 1914 the area was administered as a German colony.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] In November 1914, the islands were occupied by troops of the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed from the SS *Siar*.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] A few shots fired from a machine gun on *Siar* over the heads of the tiny German garrison at Lorengau were the last shots fired in the battle.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] After the war, the islands were governed by the Commonwealth of Australia under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Japanese troops landed on Manus Island on 7 April 1942.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] In 1944, Japanese forces occupying the islands were attacked and defeated by Allied forces in Operation Brewer.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Subsequently, a large American airbase and Manus Naval Base was built at Lombrum near Lorengau.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] Following Papuan independence in 1975, the Admiralty Islands became part of Papua New Guinea.
[src:banting-boat/admiralty-islands] They became the Manus Province of the Islands Region in Papua New Guinea.
[src:banting-boat/alingano-maisu] The concept for *Alingano Maisu* came about in 2001 when two Hawaiian voyaging groups, the Polynesian Voyaging Society and Na Kalai Waʻa Moku o Hawaiʻi, met with Piailug.
[src:banting-boat/alingano-maisu] The two hulls of the 56-foot (17 m) vessel were fabricated by the Friends of *Hōkūleʻa* and *Hawaiʻiloa* on Oʻahu and shipped to the Island of Hawaiʻi where Na Kalai Waʻa completed construction of the canoe.
[src:banting-boat/alingano-maisu] The Polynesian Voyaging Society provided much of the funding for the voyaging aspect of the project as well as an escort boat to help sail the canoe to Satawal.
[src:banting-boat/alingano-maisu] The canoe is home-ported on the island of Yap under the command of Piailug's son, Sesario Sewralur.
[src:banting-boat/alingano-maisu] Accompanied by *Hōkūleʻa*, the *Maisu* left Kawaihae, Hawaii, on January 18, 2007.
[src:banting-boat/alingano-maisu] After stops in the Marshall Islands, Pohnpei, and Chuuk, the Maisu reached Satawal on March 15, 2007.
[src:banting-boat/alingano-maisu] On March 18, while on Satawal, five native Hawaiian navigators on the voyage were inducted into pwo, a sacred Micronesian brotherhood of master navigators.
[src:banting-boat/alingano-maisu] In June 2008, Palau Community College announced that there will be a one-year program in traditional non-instrumental navigation on the *Alingano Maisu* under Sesario Sewralur.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The **New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa** is a maritime museum in Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] It is located on Hobson Wharf, adjacent to the Viaduct Harbour in central Auckland.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] It houses exhibitions spanning New Zealand's maritime history, from the first Polynesian explorers and settlers to modern day triumphs at the America's Cup.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The museum focuses on maritime stories of both the Auckland Region and New Zealand, with displays covering topics including immigration, trade, design, innovation, leisure, maritime history, Polynesian voyagers, and the history of the America's Cup.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In addition to displays and art exhibitions, the New Zealand Maritime Museum collections include historic and cultural artifacts, replicas and working heritage vessels.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The New Zealand Maritime Museum is located on Hobson Wharf on the Auckland waterfront, adjacent to the Viaduct Basin and Princes Wharf.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The entrance of the museum incorporates the Launchman's Building, a structure built in 1920 which formerly housed a number of small boating companies.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The old Launchman's Building (Launch Offices) gained a Category II listing from Heritage New Zealand in 1981.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The main section of the maritime museum in an industrial-inspired structure located on Hobson Wharf.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] Heritage vessels owned by the museum are moored at the museum marina, and launched for sailings around the Waitematā Harbour.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In 2010, the building won the Auckland Architecture Awards by the New Zealand Institute of Architects.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] Located outside of the Maritime Museum's entrance is *KZ1*, a yacht built to compete in the 1988 America's Cup, gifted to the museum by Fay Richwhite in 1990.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] Currently known as New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, the museum opened in 1993 as Hobson Wharf: Auckland Maritime Museum.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In 1996, the museum was renamed the New Zealand National Maritime Museum, a name given by Prime Minister Jim Bolger.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The museum rebranded as Voyager New Zealand Maritime Museum in November 2009, in order to reflect the museum's focus on exploration and discovery.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The organisation's current name, New Zealand Maritime Museum Hui Te Ananui a Tangaroa, was adopted in 2014.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The organisation's Māori language name, Hui te Ananui a Tangaroa, was gifted by Hugh Kāwharu of Ngāti Whātua Ōrākei, and means "the Dwelling of Tangaroa", the atua of the oceans.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The establishment of a maritime history museum in Auckland began as a proposal by members of the Auckland Maritime Society, including Bill Laxon, Bob Hawkins, Cliff Hawkins and John Street, and by former members of the Auckland Harbour Board and Union Steam Ship Company.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The society had been established in 1958 as a section of the Auckland Institute and Museum, focused on promoting the study of ships.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In 1973, the society explored the possibility of establishing a maritime museum on the shores of Lake Pupuke, which was found to be unsuitable.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In November 1981, the Auckland Maritime Museum was established as a charitable trust.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The Auckland Ferry Terminal, where the museum had been storing archival materials, was explored as a potential site for the museum, but due to the cost of renovations this was decided against.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In 1984, the museum appointed a director, Gordon Stevenson, former director of the Queen Elizabeth II Army Memorial Museum, and had begun exploring the possibility of using sheds on Princes Wharf.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] Plans for a smaller Princes Wharf museum were halted when the Auckland Harbour Board decided to redevelop Hobson Wharf, with the museum becoming a major part of the redevelopment.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In 1989, Rodney Wilson was appointed as the new director for the museum, who led fundraising efforts to establish the institution.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] Plans for the museum at Hobson Wharf were announced in February 1989, with construction on the museum beginning in mid-1992.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The museum opened in August 1993, at an estimated cost of NZ$11.1 million.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] Many of the early maritime collections were long-term loans from Auckland War Memorial Museum, or donated items by members of the Auckland Maritime Society.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] While originally focusing on Auckland, the museum later expanded to become a national maritime museum.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] By 1996, financial difficulties led to staff redundancies at the museum, with museum director Richard Cassels resigning during the financial difficulties in 1998.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In 2001, the New Zealand Government funded the Pacific Discovery Experience, a virtual reality exhibition depicting both the discovery of New Zealand by Polynesian peoples, and the later discovery by Europeans.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] A NZ$8 million extension to the northern end of the museum was built in 2009 to house a permanent exhibition, *Blue Water, Black Magic*, about Sir Peter Blake.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] It includes the original *NZL 32* (*Black Magic*).
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] *Blue Water, Black Magic* was developed in collaboration with Te Papa and Blake's daughter Sarah-Jane Blake.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In 2010, an extension was added to the museum, housing an exhibition to New Zealand yachting which includes *NZL 32*, the yacht which won the 1995 America's Cup, suspended in the centre of the space.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] By 2018, the museum received approximately 160,000 annual visitors.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The museum was run by New Zealand National Maritime Museum Trust Board until March 2018, when it became a part of Regional Facilities Auckland, an Auckland Council-controlled organisation.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The organisation is now run by Tātaki Auckland Unlimited, the economic development agency of Auckland.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In 2008, the Auckland Regional Amenities Funding Act was established, which ensured that funding for the New Zealand Maritime Museum was spread across all local councils in the Auckland Region.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] As of 2021, funding for the organisation primarily comes from the Auckland Council.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The first director of the Auckland Maritime Museum Trust was Gordon Stevenson, who was employed in January 1985.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] Rodney Wilson became the museum director in 1989, who was the director of the museum when it opened in 1993.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In 1994, Wilson left to become the director of the Auckland War Memorial Museum.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] Wilson was replaced by Richard Cassels in the same year, who left in 1998.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] Cassels was followed by chief executive Larry Robbins in 1999, Craig Hobbs in 2007, and Paul Evans in 2008.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] By 2013, Murray Reade had become the chief executive officer.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In 2013, former director of Toitū Otago Settlers Museum, Linda Wigley, became the director of the maritime museum, overseeing the redevelopment of the museum until her resignation in June 2014.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The current director of the maritime museum, Vincent Lipanovich, has held the position since 2015.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In 2018, the institution had 166 volunteers, working as tour guides, maintenance and operational crew for heritage vessels, model makers and learning programme assistants.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] Since 2003, personnel from the Royal New Zealand Navy have been occasionally seconded to the museum to assist with maintenance of the ships and exhibition objects.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] In addition, the museum holds collection items focusing on subjects including whaling, modern commercial shipping, lifeboat, pilotage and coastguard services, marine surveying, maritime arts and crafts and maritime recreation.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The museum also operates *Aotearoa One*, launched 2013, described on the museum's website as "a modern take on a traditional waka", which no longer has scheduled sailings.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The museum previously operated the *Rapaki steam crane*, a 1926 floating steam crane, built at Paisley in Scotland for the Lyttelton Harbour Board, which was permanently removed and dismantled in December 2018.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The vessel had been used in active service for three years during World War II, being used to support the United States Navy at New Caledonia.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] The museum has a collection of over 130 watercraft, including the 1933 John L.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] Hacker-designed mahogany and kauri speedboat *Jon-El*, *The Frances*, an early 20th century vessel owned by the Shakespear family, and Paul Caffyn's kayak *Isadora*.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] Other vessels include the *Tainui*, an 1860 whaling vessel, P-class sailing dinghies designed by Harry Highet, *Mammoth*, a moth-class dinghy, and the Karlich hull used by Olympic Gold medalist rowers, the 1972 New Zealand eight.
[src:banting-boat/aotearoa-one] *Tatarai*, a Baurua voyager canoe from Kiribati built in 1976 by Kiribati islanders and photographer Jim Siers using traditional methods, and sailed from Kiribati to Fiji in 1976, is also held in the museum's collections.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] Apilan is a native Malay word, not descended from any foreign word.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] It is also a standalone word, because the syllable is api-lan instead of apil-an.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] The term comes from Malay word *kota* which in turn comes from the Sanskrit word कोट्ट (kota) which means fort, fortress, castle, fortified house, fortification, works, city, town, or place encircled by walls.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] The word *mara* may come from Malay word meaning "appear before", "forward", "come", "moved to the front", "forward", and "advanced".
[src:banting-boat/apilan] Thus it can be interpreted as "breastwork before a cannon" or "breastwork at the front".
[src:banting-boat/apilan] According to the Great Indonesian Dictionary (KBBI), kota mara means (1) Wall on a ship to protect men mounting the cannon (2) Terrace or wall over a castle which a cannon is mounted.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] Warington Smyth, kota mara means transverse deck bulkhead at stem and stern (of a ship).
[src:banting-boat/apilan] *Benteng* itself means fort, battery, or redoubt.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] Singapore resident John Crawfurd recorded Malay piracy near Singapore waters.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] The Malay pirate ships of the time were 40–50 feet (12–15 m) long with 15-foot (4.6 m) beam.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] The decks were made of split *nibong* wood.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] Smaller pirate craft put up thick plank bulwarks [apilan] when fighting, while larger ones like those of the Lanun people had bamboo ledges hanging over their gunwales, with a protecting breastwork [kota mara] of plaited rattan about 3 feet (0.91 meters) high.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] A crew might consist of 20–30 men, augmented with oarsmen of captured slaves.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] Small craft would have nine oars per side; larger ones would be double-banked, with an upper tier of oarsmen seated on the bulwark projection hidden behind rattan breastwork.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] Pirate armament included a stockade near the bow, with iron or brass 4-pounders, and another stockade aft, generally with two swivel guns.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] They also might have four or five brass swivels, or rantaka, on each side.
[src:banting-boat/apilan] They have bamboo shields, and were armed with spears, keris, muskets and other firearms they could get.
[src:banting-boat/armadahan] The single outrigger float (*palangoy*) on the starboard side was either two bamboo poles lashed together or a flattened elongated beam.
[src:banting-boat/armadahan] It was connected to the hull by a length of bamboo around 6 m (20 ft) long, known as the *batangan*.
[src:banting-boat/armadahan] It also featured a counter-balance beam projecting off the port side known as the *paltek*.
[src:banting-boat/armadahan] The *batangan* is connected to the hull by a wooden outrigger beam collar, with braces on the forward, cross, and aft.
[src:banting-boat/armadahan] At the stern is a small socket for the rudder tiller.
[src:banting-boat/armadahan] Three or four other small holes are also drilled along the midcenter of the dugout to let the water enter the craft, allowing live fish to be stored in the hull when fishing.
[src:banting-boat/armadahan] These holes are also used to drain the craft when beached.
[src:banting-boat/armadahan] Each boat also has a cooking area on the aft, usually a wood or kerosene portable stove.
[src:banting-boat/armadahan] In modern times, these types of boats are usually motorized or paddled.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] They range from small dugout canoes to large lashed-lug plank-built vessels.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] Their hull configurations include monohulls as well as catamarans and outrigger boats (single-outrigger boats and trimarans).
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] Traditional sail types include a variety of distinctively Austronesian crab-claw and tanja configurations, though modern vessels are typically motorized.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] These vessels allowed the migrations of the Austronesian peoples during the Austronesian expansion (starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC from Taiwan and Island Southeast Asia) throughout the islands of the Indo-Pacific, reaching as far as Madagascar, New Zealand, and Easter Island.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] They were also used to establish trading routes, including the Austronesian maritime trade network which formed the maritime leg of the spice trade and later, the maritime silk road.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] Austronesians used distinctive sailing technologies, namely the catamaran, the outrigger ship, tanja sail and the crab claw sail.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] This allowed them to colonize a large part of the Indo-Pacific region during the Austronesian expansion starting at around 3000 to 1500 BC, and ending with the colonization of Easter Island and New Zealand in the 10th to 13th centuries AD.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] Prior to the 16th century Colonial Era, Austronesians were the most widespread ethnolinguistic group, spanning half the planet from Easter Island in the eastern Pacific Ocean to Madagascar in the western Indian Ocean.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] They also established vast maritime trading networks, among which is the Neolithic precursor to what would become the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The simplest form of all ancestral Austronesian boats had five parts.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The bottom part consists of a single piece of hollowed-out log.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] At the sides were two planks, and two horseshoe-shaped wood pieces formed the prow and stern.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] These were fitted tightly together edge-to-edge by sewing or with dowels inserted into holes in between, and then lashed to each other with ropes (made from rattan or fibre) wrapped around protruding lugs on the planks.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] This characteristic and ancient Austronesian boatbuilding practice is known as the "lashed-lug" technique.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] They were commonly caulked with pastes made from various plants as well as tapa bark and fibres which would expand when wet, further tightening joints and making the hull watertight.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] They formed the shell of the boat, which was then reinforced by horizontal ribs.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] Shipwrecks of Austronesian ships can be identified from this construction, as well as the absence of metal nails.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] Austronesian ships traditionally had no central rudders but were instead steered using an oar on one side.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] They also independently developed various sail types during the Neolithic, beginning with the crab claw sail (more usually called the "oceanic lateen" or the "oceanic sprit") at around 1500 BCE.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] They are used throughout the range of the Austronesian Expansion, from Maritime Southeast Asia, to Micronesia, Island Melanesia, Polynesia, and Madagascar.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] Crab claw sails are rigged fore-and-aft and can be tilted and rotated relative to the wind.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] They evolved from V-shaped perpendicular square sails in which the two spars converge at the base of the hull.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The simplest form of the crab claw sail (also with the widest distribution) is composed of a triangular sail supported by two light spars (sometimes erroneously called "sprits") on each side.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] They were originally mastless, and the entire assembly was taken down when the sails were lowered.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] Austronesian rigs were used for double-canoe (catamaran), single-outrigger (on the windward side), or double-outrigger boat configurations, in addition to monohulls.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] There are several distinct types of crab claw rigs, but unlike western rigs, they do not have fixed conventional names.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The need to propel larger and more heavily laden boats led to the increase in vertical sail.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] However this introduced more instability to the vessels.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] In addition to the unique invention of outriggers to solve this, the sails were also leaned backwards and the converging point moved further forward on the hull.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] This new configuration required a loose "prop" in the middle of the hull to hold the spars up, as well as rope supports on the windward side.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] This allowed more sail area (and thus more power) while keeping the center of effort low and thus making the boats more stable.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The prop was later converted into fixed or removable canted masts where the spars of the sails were actually suspended by a halyard from the masthead.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] This type of sail is most refined in Micronesian proas which could reach very high speeds.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] These configurations are sometimes known as the "crane sprit" or the "crane spritsail".
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] Micronesian, Island Melanesian, and Polynesian single-outrigger vessels also used the canted mast configuration to uniquely develop shunting.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] In shunting vessels, both ends are alike, and the boat is sailed in either direction, but it has a fixed leeward side and a windward side.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The boat is shunted from beam reach to beam reach to change direction, with the wind over the side, a low-force procedure.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The bottom corner of the crab claw sail is moved to the other end, which becomes the bow as the boat sets off back the way it came.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The mast usually hinges, adjusting the rake or angle of the mast.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The crab claw configuration used on these vessels is a low-stress rig, which can be built with simple tools and low-tech materials, but it is extremely fast.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] On a beam reach, it may be the fastest simple rig.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] Another evolution of the basic crab claw sail is the conversion of the upper spar into a fixed mast.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] In Polynesia, this gave the sail more height while also making it narrower, giving it a shape reminiscent of crab pincers (hence "crab claw" sail).
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] This was also usually accompanied by the lower spar becoming more curved.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The conversion of the prop to a fixed mast in the crab claw sail led to the much later invention of the tanja sail (also known variously and misleadingly as the canted square sail, canted rectangular sail, boomed lugsail, or balance lugsail).
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] Tanja sails were rigged similarly to crab claw sails and also had spars on both the head and the foot of the sails; but they were square or rectangular with the spars not converging into a point.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] They are generally mounted on one or two (rarely three or more) bipod or tripod masts, usually made from thick bamboo.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The masts have curved heads with grooves for attaching the halyards.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The lower part of two of the bamboo poles of the mast assembly have holes that are fitted unto the ends of a cross-wise length of timber on the deck, functioning like a hinge.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The forward part of the mast assembly had a forelock.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] By unlocking it, the mast can be lowered across the ship.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] Despite the similarity of its appearance to western square rigs, the tanja is a fore-and-aft rig similar to a lugsail.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The sail was suspended from the upper spar ("yard"), while the lower spar functioned like a boom.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] When set fore-and-aft, the spars extend forward of the mast by about a third of their lengths.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] When running before the wind, they are set perpendicular to the hull, similar to a square rig.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The sail can be rotated around the mast (lessening the need for steering with the rudders) and tilted to move the center of pull forward or aft.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The sail can even be tilted completely horizontally, becoming wing-like, to lift the bow above incoming waves.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The sail is reefed by rolling it around the lower spar.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] In addition to the tanja sails, ships with the tanja rigs also have bowsprits set with a quadrilateral headsail, sometimes also canted as depicted in the Borobudur ships.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] In the colonial era, these were replaced by triangular western-style jibs (often several in later periods), and the tanja sails themselves were slowly replaced with western rigs like gaff rigs.
[src:banting-boat/austronesian-vessels] The following is an incomplete list of traditional Austronesian vessels.
[src:banting-boat/banting-boat] In Johor, they are dugout canoe with long, sharp, hollow bow, with hollow, sharp floor.
[src:banting-boat/banting-boat] Banting is an open boat, with the inside of gunwales or ribbands fitted with holes for thole pins.
[src:banting-boat/banting-boat] It has two masts and bowsprit; carries two loosefooted balance lug (or settee) sails and small jib.
[src:banting-boat/banting-boat] Mitman recorded a banting's dimensions as follows: 33 ft 4 in (10.16 m) LOA; 5 ft 10 in (1.78 m) width; 2 ft 11 in (0.89 m) depth.
[src:banting-boat/banting-boat] The bowsprit protrude 10 in (25 cm) over the bow; the foremast is 10 ft 10 in (3.30 m) above gunwale.
[src:banting-boat/banting-boat] The yard of foresail is 16 ft 6.75 in (5.0483 m) in length.
[src:banting-boat/banting-boat] The mainmast is 12 ft 8.5 in (3.874 m) above the gunwale, with 20 ft 10 in (6.35 m) yard.
[src:banting-boat/banting-boat] Warington Smyth stated that the banting was frequently used by traders from Aceh; he further describes the boat as a two-masted trader type, built of giam wood.
[src:banting-boat/banting-boat] The boat's dimension was 90 feet (27 m) long, 27 feet (8.2 m) wide, 7 feet (2.1 m) depth, 2 ft (61 cm) freeboard; it had a capacity of 12 koyan (29 tons) and the number of on-board crew was 6.
[src:banting-boat/banting-boat] The length of the mainmast was 50 feet (15 m).
